<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="56" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,583,608]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Pronotum.</emphasis>
Form trapezoidal, smooth, shiny, width greater than length, with two distinct depressions anterolaterally. Lateral edges rounded delimited with fine borders. Borders impunctate, non–crenulated, base not bordered. Anterior angles obtuse, posterior angles right to obtuse. Pronotal surface lacking a longitudinal depression and uniformly covered with regular round punctures with yellow setae located peripherally (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1431,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–81" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1637,1660]" captionTargetBox="[171,1423,205,1613]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[171,1423,205,1613]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 76–81. Punctuation of the base of pronotum of Macroderes species. 76, M. cederbergensis Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 77, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 78, M. oreatus Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 79, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species; 80, M. soleiana Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 81, M. leipoldti Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606198/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Figs. 77</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,183,728,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–87" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1505,1528]" captionTargetBox="[316,1276,406,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[316,1276,406,1475]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 82–87. Pronotum punctures shape of Macroderes species. 82, M. tourtosus Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 83, M. cederbergensis Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 84, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 85, M. leipoldti Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 86, M. oreatus Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 87, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606200/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">84</figureCitation>
). Punctures spaced by 2–4 times their own diameter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,282,764,789]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Elytra.</emphasis>
Elytral intervals convex, shiny, densely punctate with small round punctures. Punctures separated by shiny elevated areas by approximately 1–4 their own puncture diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1105,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–93" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1292,1315]" captionTargetBox="[316,1276,183,1264]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[316,1276,183,1264]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 88–93. Pronotum punctures shape (88, 89) and sculpture of second elytra intervals (90–93) of Macroderes species. 88, M. soleiana Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 89, M. tourtosus Abdalla and Scholtz, new species; 90, M. minutus Frolov and Scholtz, 2005; 91, M. greeni (Kirby, 1818); 92, M. politulus Preudhomme de Borre, 1880; 93, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606202/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Fig. 93</figureCitation>
). Striae punctate with small punctures with short yellow setae/spaced by 2–4 punctures diameter, stria 9 closest to stria 10 about 2/3 the length of elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" box="[199,1381,908,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,908,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Aedeagus.</emphasis>
Sclerite of internal sac with long lateral process and rather short and strait basal part (
<figureCitation box="[1284,1368,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–39" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1343,1366]" captionTargetBox="[323,1250,205,1286]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[323,1283,195,1303]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 24–39. Internal sac of aedeagus (24), aedeagus (25) and internal sac sclerite (26-39) of Macroderes species. 26, M. endroedyi Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 27, M. amplior Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 28, M. bias (Olivier, 1789); 29, M. cederbergensis Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 30, M. cornutus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 31, M. foveatus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 32, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 33, M. leipoldti Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 34, M. mutilans Kolbe, 1908; 35, M. namakwanus Frolov &amp; Scholtz, 2005; 36, M. oreatus Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 37, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species; 38, M. soleiana Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 39, M. tourtosus Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606178/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,943,968]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Size range.</emphasis>
Males length: 
<quantity box="[510,664,944,968]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.75" metricValueMax="10.1" metricValueMin="9.4" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="9.75" valueMax="10.1" valueMin="9.4">9.4–10.1 mm</quantity>
, width: 
<quantity box="[760,902,943,968]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.9" metricValueMax="7.1" metricValueMin="6.7" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="6.9" valueMax="7.1" valueMin="6.7">6.7–7.1 mm</quantity>
; females length: 
<quantity box="[1101,1256,943,968]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.899999999999999" metricValueMax="10.6" metricValueMin="9.2" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="9.899999999999999" valueMax="10.6" valueMin="9.2">9.2–10.6 mm</quantity>
, width: 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.949999999999999" metricValueMax="7.3" metricValueMin="6.6" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" unit="mm" value="6.949999999999999" valueMax="7.3" valueMin="6.6">6.6–7.3 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1015,1040]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Female.</emphasis>
Female differs from male by having well developed tubercle in the middle of the frontoclypeal suture as well as less excavated pronotum anteriolaterally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="56" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1087,1112]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species name reflects the Afrikaans name, 
<emphasis box="[946,1038,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">gifboom</emphasis>
, of the evergreen Fynbos shrub 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gaertn.) Lamb. &amp; Vahl" authorityName="Lamb. &amp; Vahl" baseAuthorityName="Gaertn." box="[151,662,1124,1149]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Picrodendraceae" genus="Hyaenanche" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="globosa">
<emphasis box="[151,387,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Hyaenanche globosa</emphasis>
(Gaertn.) Lamb. &amp; Vahl
</taxonomicName>
which is endemic to the Gifberg area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="56" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,465,1159,1184]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Harold /" authorityYear="1877" box="[836,953,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Macroderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis box="[836,953,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">M. nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a pronotum with regular round punctures (
<figureCitation box="[276,371,1196,1221]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–81" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1637,1660]" captionTargetBox="[171,1423,205,1613]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[171,1423,205,1613]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 76–81. Punctuation of the base of pronotum of Macroderes species. 76, M. cederbergensis Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 77, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 78, M. oreatus Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 79, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species; 80, M. soleiana Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 81, M. leipoldti Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606198/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Figs. 77</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[385,416,1196,1220]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–87" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1505,1528]" captionTargetBox="[316,1276,406,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[316,1276,406,1475]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 82–87. Pronotum punctures shape of Macroderes species. 82, M. tourtosus Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 83, M. cederbergensis Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 84, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species; 85, M. leipoldti Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 86, M. oreatus Abdalla &amp; Deschodt, new species; 87, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606200/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">84</figureCitation>
), however the pronotum is more convex and the whole body shinier than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Harold /" authorityYear="1877" box="[1259,1373,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Macroderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis box="[1259,1373,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">M. nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1688,1711]" captionTargetBox="[314,1215,431,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[309,1269,403,1653]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Habitus of Macroderes species. 15, M. politulus Preudhomme de Borre, 1880; 16, M. undulatus Preudhomme de Borre, 1880; 17, M. porselinus Abdalla, new species; 18, M. gifboomi Abdalla &amp; Scholtz, new species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606174/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="56" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,1400]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1268,1293]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Habitat and distribution.</emphasis>
This species was collected from the base of the Gifberg (
<figureCitation box="[1142,1210,1268,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1574,1596]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution map of Macroderes species." pageId="15" pageNumber="56">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) at the northern end of the Bokkeveld Escarpment Mountain Plateau just south of Vanrhynsdorp. These mountains consist of Bokkeveld Sandstone Fynbos (
<bibRefCitation author="Mucina, L. &amp; Rutherford, M. C." box="[378,706,1340,1365]" pageId="15" pageNumber="56" pagination="1 - 807" refId="ref21930" refString="Mucina, L. &amp; Rutherford, M. C. (Eds.) (2006) The Vegetation of South Africa, Lesotho and Swaziland. Strelitzia, 19, 1 - 807." type="journal article" year="2006">Mucina &amp; Rutherford 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The habitat is very rocky with shallow soil, poor in mineral content.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
